ely on archival material, this book shows how the language of rights, like that of "civilization" and "modernity," became an important part of the discourses deployed to rationalize and legitimize empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHuman rightszAfrica, Sub-SaharanxHistoryy19th century. 0aHuman rightszAfrica, Sub-SaharanxHistoryy20th century. 0aLawzAfrica, Sub-SaharanxHistoryy19th century. 0aLawzAfrica, Sub-SaharanxHistoryy20th century. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079148092240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791480922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791480922/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles